sect2.para:
The issue of confidentiality
            confidentiality
          is serious and complex with many potential ramifications. It can be tricky to navigate and must be handled with care. One simple rule of thumb is to avoid saying anything to anyone about the client that the clinician would be uncomfortable saying to them in front of the client, the client’s attorney, and the clinician’s supervisor. Whereas the intent of this section was to alert clinicians to the primary issues, for more in-depth coverage of confidentiality
            confidentiality
          (and other key ethical issues), the interested reader is referred to Fisher (
            2022
         ), Knapp and Fingerhut (
            2023
         ), Pope et al., (
            2021
         ), and the Ethical Principles of Psychologists and Code of Conduct (APA, 
            2017
         ). Now, let’s turn to some common therapeutic factors in interviewing and some key skills related to effective interviewing.
